english:
  title: A Farewell Message for Scholar Lee
  author: Sung Gan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Scholar Lee Gyeong is the nephew of my elder cousin, the Provincial Governor. For this reason, he calls me brother, and I call him younger brother. In the summer of the Imsin year, he was to accompany the Governor to the capital. As his departure drew near, he asked me twice and thrice for words of parting, saying: "I am devoted to books—some even mock me for this excess—yet my resolve remains unchanged. On this journey, I seek to search widely and investigate thoroughly, to fulfill my long-held aspirations. What do you think of this, brother?"

    I replied: "Admirable indeed is your determination! Now, those who travel to the capital—do they not all rush about the marketplace, filling their coffers with whatever their hearts desire? Yet you pursue something altogether different. Surely this sets you a step above the rest. Still, the abundance of texts stretches from the age of Fuxi down to our own time—vast as the sea, thick as clouds. Every student of books gains understanding according to their own inclinations. But the cultivated person is not thus. They expand their spirit to encompass the minutest details and concentrate their wisdom to grasp the essential principles, so that both the refined and the coarse, the root and the branches, all fall within their comprehension.

    Consider a mountain forest where timber lies scattered in confusion, trees standing thick and tangled. When common folk enter such a place, each takes only what their strength allows, cutting only what serves their immediate need. But when a true craftsman surveys the same forest, he sees perfectly: the great timber for beams, the slender for pipes, the short for doorposts, the long for hinges. The round finds its purpose, the straight its place, the square its use, the curved its fitting. Nothing lacks its proper station. Order emerges from chaos; pattern arises from confusion. Why is this? Because his perception is vast and his skill is precise.

    Now, when you pursue learning from books, will you trace the classics of the sages to establish the great foundations first, thereby grasping the principles of order and coherence—as the craftsman does? Or will you merely gather fragments here and there, satisfied with your own narrow corner, seeking nothing beyond? This choice rests with you alone, not with me. This is for you to consider and decide.

    As for those subtle and profound mysteries, the detailed steps of practice—these we shall explore when you return. On a snowy night, by lamplight, sitting together by the fire, we shall open what treasures you have gathered and engage in earnest discussion of one or two points.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Imsin year (임신년) refers to a specific year in the traditional East Asian sexagenary cycle, likely during the Joseon period.
  - key: ''
    value: Fuxi (복희) is a legendary sage-king in Chinese tradition, representing the distant past of civilization.
  - key: ''
    value: The craftsman (匠石) and the forest analogy illustrate how proper learning requires both breadth of knowledge and discernment of fundamental principles, not mere accumulation of information.
